description.plain:
With their thoroughly modern disco sound — a blend of house, funk, electro and techno — this French duo was one of the biggest electronic music acts of the late 1990s and 2000s. Guy Manuel de Homem-Christo and Thomas Bangalter wore shiny droid costumes at every live show (and only allowed themselves to be photographed in said costumes) but their music was only sometimes robotic: Daft Punk were as influenced by rock bands like AC/DC as they were by classic disco acts (Chic’s Nile Rodgers even collaborated with them for their hit 2013 single, “Get Lucky”). Not only were they prolific creators, but some of the best collaborators in the industry, producing for and working alongside artists such as Kanye West and The Weeknd.

On 22 February 2021, Daft Punk announced their retirement through a video titled “Epilogue,” featuring footage from their 2004 film Electroma and the orchestral version of “Touch”. It marks an end to the incredible journey they had in influencing the world of music, with just four studio albums released over the course of 28 years.

description.plain: The lead single from Daft Punk’s fourth and final studio album, Random Access Memories, “Get Lucky” was first teased in snippets on Saturday Night Live. It peaked in the top 3 in every country it charted in and, because of its performance in the United States, got the duo their first song to reach the top 10 on the Billboard charts. According to an interview with Pitchfork, the original version featured the Wurlitzer electronic piano, but because of the revisions, took 18 months to complete from start to finish.

songs.title: Touch

description.plain:
Featuring vocals from renowned singer-songwriter Paul Williams, this song marks the midpoint of Random Access Memories and seems to possibly continue where “Within” left off.

Opening with a bizarre segment consisting of warped sines and synths, this track takes cues from the work of the late electronic composer Karlheinz Stockhausen before taking listeners on a genre-bending ride that spans electronic, ragtime, and orchestral music.

Paul’s vocals seep in and out of the song, longing for not only the physical, but emotional “touch” of other people after an extended period of time in isolation. The speaker may have had plenty of time to think and reflect while in their lonesome, but after looking inside themselves, they realize that they are missing something, and need “something more” to be fulfilled and feel truly human.
